00:00.000 --> 00:06.360
Imagine you are, you're standing right in the middle of this massive, impossibly complex labyrinth.

00:06.540 --> 00:06.780
Right.

00:06.980 --> 00:14.060
You take a step forward and you expect the stone walls to just, you know, sit there rigid and permanent like walls usually do.

00:14.160 --> 00:15.360
Yeah, like normal architecture.

00:15.540 --> 00:15.940
Exactly.

00:16.400 --> 00:24.860
But instead, the moment your foot hits the ground, the walls behind you just violently collapse and it doesn't stop there.

00:24.920 --> 00:25.620
It keeps going.

00:25.760 --> 00:25.920
Right.

00:25.920 --> 00:37.160
The doorways ahead of you physically warp, they change shape, their entire architecture alters based on the exact specific path you just took to get to where you're standing right now.

00:37.360 --> 00:38.680
It's a wild visual.

00:38.960 --> 00:39.520
It is.

00:39.600 --> 00:45.240
Because if you had taken like one different turn three miles back, the door in front of you right now wouldn't even exist.

00:45.420 --> 00:47.540
Yeah, it's a completely disorienting image.

00:47.800 --> 00:51.260
But honestly, it captures the core of what we are dealing with today.

00:51.340 --> 00:52.140
It really does.

00:52.140 --> 00:55.740
Because we usually think of a system's current state as something we can isolate.

00:56.260 --> 01:00.220
You know, something we can just measure right now, completely independent of its past.

01:00.500 --> 01:01.340
Like taking a snapshot.

01:01.780 --> 01:02.180
Exactly.

01:02.320 --> 01:03.340
Just a static snapshot.

01:03.620 --> 01:08.100
But in this maze you're describing, your history is a physical weight.

01:08.500 --> 01:13.300
It is actively reconstructing the boundaries of your future possibility space.

01:13.440 --> 01:16.840
And here's where it gets just completely mind bending for you listening.

01:16.980 --> 01:21.260
Because that collapsing maze, that isn't just some metaphor for a fun video game mechanic.

01:21.420 --> 01:22.120
No, not at all.

01:22.120 --> 01:33.680
According to the research we are diving into today, that collapsing maze is the exact, literal, underlying mathematical reality of how a single photon of light behaves when it hits an atom.

01:33.840 --> 01:35.260
Which is wild enough on its own.

01:35.380 --> 01:35.660
Right.

