abstract toys, Flyxion takes this exact bouncer and VIP math and claims it explains human thought.

15:25.940 --> 15:27.140
Yes, cognition itself.

15:27.200 --> 15:30.340
How your brain, the listener's brain, is working right now.

15:30.720 --> 15:33.760
Let's bring this down to the cognitive and semantic layer.

15:33.760 --> 15:41.580
To bridge abstract math to human cognition, the paper leans really heavily on Douglas Hofstadter's theories.

15:41.700 --> 15:42.540
Okay, what's his deal?

15:42.980 --> 15:46.060
Hofstadter is brilliant at deconstructing how we think.

15:46.720 --> 15:54.040
He argues that human cognition is not a rigid filing cabinet of dictionary definitions, nor is it purely formal logic.

15:54.160 --> 15:54.780
What is it, then?

15:54.780 --> 15:57.220
It is, fundamentally, an engine of analogy.

15:57.400 --> 16:00.340
A blurry attractor is the phrase the paper uses, right?

16:00.420 --> 16:00.620
Yes.

16:01.060 --> 16:03.680
Think about what a concept actually is in your mind.

16:04.280 --> 16:09.720
If I ask you to define a chair, you don't access a rigid geometric blueprint of four legs and a seat.

16:10.100 --> 16:11.200
No, of course not.

16:11.420 --> 16:13.040
Because a beanbag is a chair.

16:13.300 --> 16:15.140
A hollowed-out tree stump can be a chair.

16:15.420 --> 16:19.500
A giant plastic hand from a 1990s catalog is a chair.

16:19.760 --> 16:22.640
And yet, you instantly recognize all of them as chairs.

16:22.640 --> 16:24.320
Yeah, without even thinking about it.

16:24.480 --> 16:27.880
Hofstadter says your concept of a chair is a bundle of analogies.

16:28.920 --> 16:36.840
It's a fuzzy, blurry attractor in your mind that pulls in anything that structurally feels like it shares the invariant of something I can sit on.

16:36.940 --> 16:37.960
Okay, I like that.

16:38.040 --> 16:43.340
Hofstadter defines the central cognitive loop as the way we navigate the world using these bundles.

16:43.460 --> 16:44.500
How does the loop work?

16:44.780 --> 16:47.080
Walk me through a slow-motion example of a thought.

16:47.080 --> 16:53.480
Let's say you walk into an art gallery and you see a strange, twisting piece of metal bolted to the wall.

16:53.680 --> 16:55.260
Okay, so that is your perturbation.

16:55.440 --> 16:55.640
Right.

16:56.000 --> 17:01.740
Your brain encounters this novel situation and activates a stored conceptual chunk.

17:02.440 --> 17:04.920
Maybe your blurry concept of a shelf.

17:05.440 --> 17:05.840
Okay.

17:05.840 --> 17:08.560
You unpack that concept into your working memory.

17:09.140 --> 17:14.300
You look at the twisted metal and you experience what Hofstadter calls analogical slippage.

17:14.500 --> 17:14.880
Slippage.

17:14.980 --> 17:20.520
Like, my brain is trying to map the twisted metal onto the idea of a shelf, but the mapping isn't perfectly smooth.

17:20.720 --> 17:21.780
It slips around a bit.

17:22.120 --> 17:22.560
Exactly.

17:22.860 --> 17:24.360
You realize they aren't identical.

17:24.740 --> 17:26.820
A normal shelf is flat wood.

17:27.120 --> 17:28.000
This is angled metal.

17:28.100 --> 17:28.360
Right.

17:28.640 --> 17:30.920
But your brain finds a shared invariant.

17:31.780 --> 17:35.280
They both project from a wall and could hold a lightweight object.

17:35.280 --> 17:36.200
Oh, wow.

17:36.360 --> 17:43.700
You map the new object onto the old concept, violently reorganizing your internal definition of what a shelf can look like.

17:43.840 --> 17:48.780
And finally, you re-chunk this new understanding into a stable thought.

17:48.940 --> 17:50.540
Oh, it's an avant-garde bookshelf.

17:50.720 --> 17:51.240
Yes.

17:51.340 --> 17:52.860
Here's where it gets really interesting.

17:53.340 --> 18:03.800
That sequence you just described, encountering the strange metal, testing it against your mental definition, altering your definition to absorb it, and reaching a new stable conclusion.

18:04.060 --> 18:04.240
Yeah.

18:04.240 --> 18:07.300
That is literally the generalized reduction operator.

18:07.720 --> 18:09.920
It maps perfectly onto the sphere pop bubbles.

18:10.100 --> 18:10.920
It really does.

18:11.020 --> 18:15.520
Your existing worldview is a massive cluster of nested geometric bubbles.

18:16.100 --> 18:17.820
My words right now are the perturbation.

18:17.980 --> 18:21.040
And my semantic understanding is the admissibility membrane.

18:21.260 --> 18:21.740
Exactly.

18:21.960 --> 18:25.980
You are constantly testing the concepts I am explaining to see if they fit your constraints.

18:26.080 --> 18:26.240
Right.

18:26.240 --> 18:29.460
If they do, your conceptual membrane collapses.

18:29.920 --> 18:36.960
You reorganize your internal topology to integrate the new idea, and you reach a new, stable, cognitive output.

18:37.160 --> 18:41.720
So every time I learn something, a bubble in my brain pops and reforms into a bigger bubble.

18:41.720 --> 18:42.420
Pretty much.

18:42.780 --> 18:49.760
But the paper cites a linguistic researcher named Johansson who takes this a step further, and it honestly feels a bit backward to me.

18:49.880 --> 18:50.960
The linguistic precedent.

18:51.200 --> 18:51.280
Yeah.

18:51.500 --> 18:59.400
Johansson proposes that language acquisition and analogy itself are fundamentally processes of reduction, not construction.

18:59.400 --> 19:03.400
It is a counterintuitive inversion of how we usually view intelligence.

19:03.500 --> 19:03.940
I'll give you that.

19:04.080 --> 19:05.240
I mean, I have to challenge this.

19:05.540 --> 19:12.960
When I think of human creativity, writing a novel, inventing a tool, a child learning to speak, I think of it as building.

19:13.460 --> 19:14.500
Sure, adding things.

19:14.580 --> 19:14.740
Yeah.

19:15.040 --> 19:17.940
I am taking small blocks and constructing a massive tower.

19:18.220 --> 19:19.880
I am adding to the universe.

19:20.440 --> 19:26.400
Are you and Johansson really telling me that human creativity is actually just destroying possibilities?

19:27.240 --> 19:27.640
I like it.

19:27.740 --> 19:28.940
Whittling things down?

19:28.940 --> 19:31.660
I know it sounds bleak, but think about the alternative.

19:32.220 --> 19:34.960
Think about the infinite deafening noise of reality.

19:35.360 --> 19:41.220
Every single millisecond, your retinas are bombarded by millions of photons of varying wavelengths.

19:41.620 --> 19:46.180
Your eardrums are vibrating with thousands of overlapping acoustic frequencies.

19:46.320 --> 19:47.300
That's a lot of data.

19:47.500 --> 19:49.880
The temperature of the air is fluctuating across your skin.

19:50.280 --> 19:58.120
If your brain tried to construct reality by paying equal attention to all of that raw, infinite data, what would happen?

19:58.120 --> 19:59.640
I'd be completely paralyzed.

19:59.740 --> 20:04.140
It would be like staring at the static on an old television set at maximum volume.

20:04.340 --> 20:05.980
I wouldn't be able to pick out a signal at all.

20:06.180 --> 20:06.300
Right.

20:06.780 --> 20:12.640
Cognition survives precisely because it is an aggressive, relentless process of reduction.

20:12.840 --> 20:13.440
Oh, I see.

20:13.440 --> 20:18.700
Continuously destroys the infinite noise by forcing it through admissibility membranes.

20:18.940 --> 20:27.060
When you realize that a Ferrari racing down a track and a cheetah sprinting across a savannah share the analogical concept of speed.

20:27.540 --> 20:27.820
Yeah.

20:28.160 --> 20:29.560
You haven't built something out of nothing.

20:29.560 --> 20:38.960
You have taken a massive, chaotic ocean of sensory data about engines, fur, tires, muscles, and asphalt, and you have violently collapsed it.

20:39.140 --> 20:43.560
You reduced all that irregularity down to a single, manageable, transportable tunk fast.

20:44.420 --> 20:44.640
Ah.

20:45.100 --> 20:49.240
Without reduction, we drown in the excess possibility of the universe.

20:49.420 --> 20:50.400
We would be overwhelmed.

20:50.520 --> 20:54.580
By destroying the irrelevant noise, the coherent signal emerges.

20:55.140 --> 20:58.400
We are basically carving the statue out of the marble block.

20:58.400 --> 21:00.000
That's a perfect metaphor.

21:00.460 --> 21:05.800
And Flyxion mathematically cements this by invoking the Curry-Howard correspondence.

21:06.020 --> 21:06.240
Okay.

21:06.400 --> 21:06.840
What's that?

21:07.080 --> 21:12.900
If we connect this to the bigger picture, Curry-Howard is one of the most profound discoveries in computer science.

21:12.980 --> 21:13.580
Oh, really?

21:13.860 --> 21:21.040
It is the rigorous mathematical proof that computer programs and logical mathematical proofs are not just similar.

21:21.460 --> 21:22.820
They are structurally identical.

21:22.820 --> 21:30.580
Wait, a computer program like the code running the web browser I use is literally the exact same thing as a mathematician writing a proof on a chalkboard?

21:30.880 --> 21:31.780
Structurally, yes.

21:32.060 --> 21:37.460
In Curry-Howard, a specific type of data in a program corresponds directly to a logical proposition.

21:37.660 --> 21:37.900
Okay.

21:38.460 --> 21:47.200
And the actual execution of the program, the software running step-by-step to find an answer, is identical to the process of normalizing mathematical proof to find the truth.

21:47.200 --> 21:49.740
So how does Flyxion map that to the human brain?

21:50.180 --> 21:54.540
By arguing that human cognition is just a generalized proof reduction process.

21:54.660 --> 21:54.960
Wow.

21:55.260 --> 22:05.420
When your brain struggles with a new concept and finally reaches an aha moment of understanding, you are experiencing the biological equivalent of a computer program successfully compiling.

22:05.660 --> 22:08.580
Or a lambda calculus function reaching its normal form.

22:08.660 --> 22:09.120
Exactly.

22:09.600 --> 22:14.780
Reaching semantic coherence in reality is mathematically identical to a proof normalizing.

22:14.780 --> 22:16.100
That is heavy.

22:16.280 --> 22:20.660
My brain is running the same core reduction software as a compiler executing code.

22:20.820 --> 22:21.360
It is.

22:21.600 --> 22:25.780
But, you know, up until now we've been dealing with layer 3 and layer 4 abstractions.

22:25.900 --> 22:26.120
Right.

22:26.320 --> 22:26.580
Theory.

22:26.860 --> 22:30.740
We're talking about math on chalkboards and philosophical theories of mind.

22:31.380 --> 22:33.580
But Flyxion claims this isn't just a metaphor.

22:34.240 --> 22:41.120
The paper explicitly states that biology is the strongest empirical pillar proving this theory exists in physical space.

22:41.520 --> 22:44.340
It is time to leave the theoretical and look at the wetware.

22:44.340 --> 22:46.660
Let's dive into Layer 1, Established Science.

22:47.220 --> 22:52.700
The paper heavily references a 2026 Nature Reviews Genetics paper by Wang, He, and Hu.

22:52.840 --> 22:54.480
Yes, on multimodal lineage tracing.

22:54.800 --> 22:55.100
Right.

22:55.280 --> 22:56.700
It's about single cell biology.

22:57.600 --> 22:59.340
Now, set the stage for me here.

22:59.900 --> 23:04.540
What is the fundamental mystery biologists are actually trying to solve when they look at a cell?

23:04.760 --> 23:05.800
They want to know two things.

23:06.600 --> 23:08.540
A cell's destiny and its history.

23:08.840 --> 23:09.140
Okay.

23:09.140 --> 23:12.500
Imagine looking at a single stem cell under a microscope.

23:13.540 --> 23:20.700
Historically, the best way to understand what that cell is doing right now is to measure its RNA, its transcriptomic profile.

23:20.880 --> 23:21.880
What does that tell you?

23:22.140 --> 23:24.400
It is incredibly high-definition data.

23:24.400 --> 23:35.760
It tells you exactly which genes are turned on, which proteins are being manufactured, and what the cell's internal machinery is doing down to the molecular level at that exact millisecond.

23:35.860 --> 23:41.120
So they basically take a 4K, ultra-high-definition photograph of the cell's factory floor.

23:41.340 --> 23:41.960
Dutifully put.

23:42.500 --> 23:45.720
But the review paper highlights a devastating limitation with this.

23:45.740 --> 23:46.100
Which is?

23:46.220 --> 23:50.000
Measuring a cell's current RNA completely underdetermines its history.

23:50.140 --> 23:50.540
What do you mean?

23:50.540 --> 23:53.500
You could have two cells sitting right next to each other in a Petri dish.

23:54.080 --> 23:58.860
You sequence their RNA, and their transcriptomic profiles are 99.9% identical.

23:59.300 --> 24:00.000
They look like twins.

24:00.280 --> 24:00.560
Okay.

24:00.700 --> 24:01.580
I see where this is going.

24:01.680 --> 24:03.660
It's the nightclub analogy all over again.

24:03.740 --> 24:06.480
It is the exact same problem manifested in biology.

24:06.780 --> 24:08.860
So club A and club B.

24:09.000 --> 24:09.320
Right.

24:10.020 --> 24:14.380
Cell A might have just arrived at this state directly from a simple progenitor cell.

24:14.380 --> 24:24.040
But cell B might have taken a wild, looping developmental detour, turning genes on and off for days before settling into this current profile.

24:24.160 --> 24:29.520
And because their histories are different, their internal constraint membranes, their epigenetics are different.

24:29.620 --> 24:30.100
Exactly.

24:30.580 --> 24:41.880
Even though they look identical right now, if you expose both cells to a new chemical signal, cell A might become a healthy heart muscle, and cell B might trigger apoptosis and self-destruct.

24:41.880 --> 24:44.900
If you only look at the snapshot, you miss the history.

24:45.140 --> 24:48.280
And if you miss the history, you cannot predict the future of the organism.

24:48.360 --> 24:49.320
That's the crux of it.

24:49.480 --> 24:53.680
This brings up a biological concept the paper calls progressive potency restriction.

24:53.940 --> 24:54.180
Yes.

24:54.560 --> 24:55.900
Let's trace the life of a cell.

24:56.120 --> 24:56.400
Okay.

24:56.620 --> 25:01.880
When a human embryo is just a fertilized egg, a zygote, that single cell is totipotent.

25:02.480 --> 25:05.120
It possesses the ultimate admissibility region.

25:05.240 --> 25:05.780
Meaning what?

25:06.000 --> 25:10.700
It has the potential to become literally any cell in the entire human body.

25:10.700 --> 25:11.040
Right.

25:11.040 --> 25:15.040
A retina, a piece of bone, a neuron in the brain.

25:15.200 --> 25:17.560
It has every single career option open to it.

25:17.660 --> 25:17.840
Right.

25:18.660 --> 25:21.840
But as it divides and grows, it has to make choices.

25:22.480 --> 25:24.780
And every choice is a permanent sacrifice.

25:24.920 --> 25:26.400
A sacrifice of potential.

25:26.660 --> 25:26.940
Yes.

25:27.380 --> 25:29.660
It receives a chemical perturbation from its neighbors.

25:30.420 --> 25:34.900
If the signal is compatible, the cell undergoes a massive internal reorganization.

25:34.960 --> 25:35.920
A collapse operator.

25:35.920 --> 25:36.560
Exactly.

25:37.180 --> 25:41.500
It physically folds up certain sections of its DNA, making them permanently inaccessible.

25:41.860 --> 25:44.360
It collapses into a new, more restricted state.

25:44.680 --> 25:49.280
So once it decides to go to medical school to be the liver cell, it permanently burns the

25:49.280 --> 25:50.720
bridge to becoming a skin cell.

25:51.240 --> 25:53.440
The admissibility region physically shrinks.

25:53.760 --> 25:56.980
Every single developmental step is a literal membrane collapse.

25:56.980 --> 26:03.560
The cell tests incoming data, accepts it, alters its own internal topology, and spits out a stable

26:03.560 --> 26:04.140
invariant.

26:04.240 --> 26:05.700
And what's the invariant in biology?

26:06.180 --> 26:08.160
The continuous viability of the organism.

26:08.480 --> 26:13.420
The cell survives because it successfully reduced its own infinite potential into a manageable,

26:13.740 --> 26:14.660
constrained identity.

26:14.660 --> 26:16.660
Okay, the math maps beautifully.

26:17.340 --> 26:22.480
But if scientists know these hidden histories exist, how do they actually track them in

26:22.480 --> 26:22.860
the lab?

26:23.160 --> 26:25.680
You said the RNA snapshot misses the history.

26:26.120 --> 26:29.360
And this is where we encounter the measurement problem of single-cell biology.

26:30.400 --> 26:37.720
The technology we use to read a cell's RNA, single-cell RNA sequencing, is inherently destructive.

26:37.920 --> 26:38.340
Destructive.

26:38.540 --> 26:38.760
Yes.

26:38.860 --> 26:42.280
To read the genetic data, you literally have to break the cell open.

26:42.280 --> 26:46.960
You dissolve its membrane, extract the RNA, and destroy the cell in the process.

26:47.300 --> 26:48.000
Wait, really?

26:48.100 --> 26:49.520
You have to kill the cell to read it?

26:49.720 --> 26:54.220
You can never observe a single cell's history over time, because the moment you look at it

26:54.220 --> 26:57.520
deeply enough to understand its state, you have ended its life.

26:57.660 --> 26:59.460
That is agonizing for a scientist.

26:59.860 --> 27:00.540
It really is.

27:00.580 --> 27:02.580
You can only ever see the final frame of the movie.

27:02.700 --> 27:06.540
How do you map a family tree if every time you look at a family member, they vanish?

27:06.940 --> 27:10.940
Well, biologists have to turn to computational deep learning frameworks.

27:10.940 --> 27:14.760
Tools with names like Lineage OT or Lineage VAE.

27:14.820 --> 27:15.020
Okay.

27:15.200 --> 27:15.880
AI tools.

27:16.160 --> 27:16.360
Right.

27:17.040 --> 27:22.580
Because they can't track one cell over time, they sequence millions of different cells at

27:22.580 --> 27:24.380
different time points, destroying them all.

27:24.580 --> 27:25.100
Wow.

27:25.360 --> 27:30.620
Then they use AI to try and mathematically reconstruct the ghost trajectories.

27:30.960 --> 27:35.520
They try to guess the hidden membrane collapses that must have happened in the dark.

27:35.660 --> 27:38.940
They are trying to draw the maze after the walls have already collapsed.

27:38.940 --> 27:44.040
That's exactly it. And this creates a massive mathematical conflict that the Wang paper

27:44.040 --> 27:46.260
calls disparate multimodality.

27:46.680 --> 27:51.160
Disparate multimodality. That sounds like an oxymoron. Break that down for me. What are

27:51.160 --> 27:52.360
the two disparate modes?

27:52.500 --> 27:54.580
It is a profound conflict of geometry.

27:54.800 --> 27:55.180
Geometry.

27:55.440 --> 28:03.080
Yeah. On one side, you have the RNA transcriptomic data. This data exists in a continuous, incredibly

28:03.080 --> 28:04.780
high-dimensional fluid space.

28:04.900 --> 28:05.620
Fluid. Okay.

28:05.620 --> 28:10.700
If you map it, cell states look like smooth clouds blending into one another. There are

28:10.700 --> 28:12.940
infinite micro-gradations between states.

28:13.060 --> 28:16.300
Like a watercolor painting where the blue slowly bleeds into the green.

28:16.440 --> 28:21.200
Perfect analogy. Now, on the other side, you have the Lineage tree, the actual historical

28:21.200 --> 28:23.520
family tree of which cell divided into which.

28:23.580 --> 28:23.820
Right.

28:24.100 --> 28:29.260
That tree is discrete. It is a rigid graph made of hard-branching forks and sharp angles.

28:29.260 --> 28:31.920
It is digital, not fluid.

28:32.320 --> 28:38.920
So the math is trying to force a smooth, continuous watercolor cloud to perfectly align with a sharp,

28:39.220 --> 28:41.360
digital-branching stick figure drawing.

28:41.560 --> 28:46.760
Exactly. Reconciling those two geometries is computationally agonizing.

28:46.820 --> 28:47.440
I can imagine.

28:47.660 --> 28:52.240
And when the math breaks down, Flyxion points out that biological models do something terrifying.

28:52.240 --> 28:57.280
They experience what the paper calls a developmental hallucination.

28:57.600 --> 28:59.440
Here's where it gets really interesting.

28:59.580 --> 29:03.020
Because when I hear hallucination, I immediately think of generative AI.

29:03.280 --> 29:03.680
Naturally.

29:03.860 --> 29:09.400
Right. If I ask a large language model to write a biography of a completely fake historical figure,

29:09.580 --> 29:13.080
say, a 16th century pirate who also invented the toaster.

29:13.200 --> 29:14.080
A classic prompt.

29:14.080 --> 29:17.240
The AI will confidently generate a five-page essay.

29:17.660 --> 29:21.880
And if you read any single sentence in that essay, it makes perfect chromatical sense.

29:22.100 --> 29:24.360
He patented the heating element in 1582.

29:24.660 --> 29:26.460
Sounds legitimate on a micro level.

29:26.680 --> 29:27.200
Exactly.

29:28.020 --> 29:30.400
Locally, the grammar is flawless.

29:30.860 --> 29:36.160
But when you zoom out and look at the entire essay, the whole thing is a factual hallucination.

29:36.520 --> 29:40.100
It violates the global constraints of historical reality.

29:40.740 --> 29:43.680
Are you telling me that computational biology models do this too?

29:44.180 --> 29:45.800
Computationally, they do exactly that.

29:45.960 --> 29:46.540
No way.

29:46.660 --> 29:50.100
When these AI models try to reconstruct the hidden histories of cells,

29:50.340 --> 29:55.080
they often assign perfectly plausible local histories to individual cells.

29:55.300 --> 29:56.620
Like the individual sentences.

29:56.760 --> 29:57.260
Exactly.

29:57.560 --> 29:59.420
The model will say, look at cell A.

29:59.900 --> 30:04.180
Based on its RNA, it makes perfect sense that it just transitioned from progenitor B.

30:04.800 --> 30:06.440
The local chemical grammar checks out.

30:06.520 --> 30:08.200
So the local sentence makes sense.

30:08.540 --> 30:12.760
But when the scientists zoom out and look at the entire reconstructed family tree of the organism,

30:12.760 --> 30:15.460
the global story is physically impossible.

30:16.040 --> 30:16.160
Wow.

30:16.540 --> 30:20.160
The implied tree might suggest a cell traveled backward in developmental time,

30:20.340 --> 30:25.340
or that it bypassed a hard epigenetic wall that we know is biologically impenetrable.

30:25.700 --> 30:30.400
The local rules were followed, but the global architecture is a hallucination.

30:30.620 --> 30:31.680
That is fascinating.

30:31.860 --> 30:34.080
The model gets completely lost in the maze.

30:34.080 --> 30:34.640
Yes.

30:34.860 --> 30:39.780
And in advanced mathematics, specifically a field called sheaf cohomology,

30:40.040 --> 30:42.940
there is a formal name for this kind of failure.

30:43.200 --> 30:43.700
What's it called?

30:44.120 --> 30:45.780
It is called a gluing obstruction.

30:46.120 --> 30:46.920
A gluing obstruction.

30:47.160 --> 30:47.360
Okay.

30:47.540 --> 30:51.180
Help me visualize sheaf cohomology without using equations, if you can.

30:51.480 --> 30:52.340
I can try.

30:52.460 --> 30:52.680
Yeah.

30:52.900 --> 30:58.200
Imagine you were trying to create a 360-degree panorama photo on your smartphone.

30:58.360 --> 30:58.660
Okay.

30:58.780 --> 30:59.620
I do that all the time.

30:59.620 --> 31:03.140
You stand in a city square and slowly pan your camera around.

31:03.440 --> 31:06.140
The phone takes dozens of individual, narrow pictures.

31:06.280 --> 31:07.640
We call these local patches.

31:07.860 --> 31:08.000
Okay.

31:08.060 --> 31:12.960
I take picture one of a cafe, picture two of the street, picture three of a park bench.

31:13.260 --> 31:18.000
Individually, every single local patch is a perfect, internally consistent photograph.

31:18.500 --> 31:22.060
But now, the software has to glue them together into a global surface.

31:22.240 --> 31:22.320
Right.

31:22.400 --> 31:23.160
Stitching them together.

31:23.280 --> 31:26.480
Imagine that while you were panning, a man was walking quickly across the square.

31:26.480 --> 31:28.680
In picture one, he is on the left.

31:28.940 --> 31:30.180
In picture two, he is on the right.

31:30.600 --> 31:31.820
In picture three, he is gone.

31:32.120 --> 31:33.120
